### Structures in C

A structure (`struct`) is a user-defined data type that groups related variables of different types under one name.

### Defining a Structure

```c
struct Person {
  char name[50];
  int age;
  float height;
};
```

### Declaring Variables

```c
struct Person person1;
struct Person person2 = {"Alice", 30, 5.6};
```

### Accessing Members

Use the dot operator `.` to access structure members.

```c
person1.age = 25;
strcpy(person1.name, "Bob");
```

### Structure Memory

Structures may contain padding bytes between members for alignment. Use `sizeof()` to get the actual size.

| Member | Size | Offset (may vary) |
|--------|------|------------------|
| `char name[50]` | 50 | 0 |
| `int age` | 4 | 52 (with padding) |
| `float height` | 4 | 56 (with padding) |

---

> **Key Point:** Structure members are accessed with `.` for variables and `->` for pointers. Structures can be passed to functions by value or by pointer.

codeExample:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

struct Student {
  char name[50];
  int age;
  float gpa;
};

int main() {
  struct Student s1;
  strcpy(s1.name, "Alice");
  s1.age = 20;
  s1.gpa = 3.8;
  printf("Name: %s\n", s1.name);
  printf("Age: %d\n", s1.age);
  printf("GPA: %.1f\n", s1.gpa);
  return 0;
}
